🧠 1. What Happens When @Transactional Runs (Internals)

When you call a transactional method:

Client → Proxy → Transaction Manager → DB

Internal Flow

Spring creates AOP Proxy

Proxy intercepts method

Opens DB transaction

Executes method

If success → COMMIT

If RuntimeException → ROLLBACK

🧪 Demo
@Service
public class TransferService {

    @Transactional
    public void transfer(Long from, Long to, double amount) {
        debit(from, amount);
        credit(to, amount);
    }
}

🧠 2. Transaction Proxy Problem (Most Asked Interview Q)
Perfect — this is one of the MOST asked Spring interview questions. Let’s make it crystal clear.

2. Transaction Proxy Problem (Self-Invocation)
Core Idea

Spring applies @Transactional using AOP Proxy, not directly on your method.

So ONLY calls that go through the Spring proxy get transaction.

If a method inside the same class calls another @Transactional method → proxy is bypassed → NO transaction.

❌ Problem Example (Self Invocation)
@Service
public class TransferService {

    public void outer() {
        inner();   // ❌ Direct call → NO proxy → NO transaction
    }

    @Transactional
    public void inner() {
        System.out.println("Transaction active?");
    }
}

What happens internally
Client → Proxy → outer()  ✔
outer() → inner() (direct call, no proxy) ❌


So inner() runs WITHOUT transaction.

How to Verify (Debug)

Add:

System.out.println(TransactionSynchronizationManager.isActualTransactionActive());


You’ll see:

false

✔ Fix #1 — Move to Another Service (Best Practice)

Spring proxy works only between beans, not inside same class.

@Service
public class InnerService {

    @Transactional
    public void inner() {
        System.out.println("Transaction ACTIVE");
    }
}

@Service
public class TransferService {

    @Autowired
    private InnerService innerService;

    public void outer() {
        innerService.inner();   // ✔ Goes through proxy → transaction works
    }
}

✔ Fix #2 — Self Injection (Proxy Call)
@Service
public class TransferService {

    @Autowired
    private TransferService self;   // Inject proxy of same bean

    public void outer() {
        self.inner();   // ✔ goes through proxy
    }

    @Transactional
    public void inner() {
        System.out.println("Transaction ACTIVE");
    }
}


⚠ Works, but not recommended in clean architecture.

✔ Fix #3 — Use TransactionTemplate (Manual Control)
@Autowired
private TransactionTemplate txTemplate;

public void outer() {
    txTemplate.execute(status -> {
        innerLogic();
        return null;
    });
}

✔ Fix #4 — Make Outer Method Transactional

If both must be transactional:

@Transactional
public void outer() {
    inner();   // Now works because outer already opened tx
}

