🧠 3. Rollback Rules (Important)
Default Rule (Most Important)

Spring ROLLS BACK only on unchecked exceptions:

✅ RuntimeException → rollback

✅ Error → rollback

❌ Checked Exception → NO rollback

Example — Default Behaviour
@Transactional
public void transfer() {
    debit();   // money deducted
    if (true) {
        throw new RuntimeException("Failure"); // ❌ RuntimeException
    }
    credit();
}


✔ Result → ROLLBACK happens → money restored

Checked Exception Case (Danger)
@Transactional
public void transfer() throws Exception {
    debit();
    if (true) {
        throw new Exception("Failure");  // ❌ Checked Exception
    }
    credit();
}


❌ Result → NO rollback → money deducted → DATA CORRUPTION

This is a very common production bug.

Fix — Force Rollback for Checked Exception
@Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)
public void transfer() throws Exception {
    debit();
    throw new Exception("Failure");
}


✔ Now rollback will happen.

Ignore Rollback for Some Exceptions

Sometimes you don’t want rollback (rare but useful).

@Transactional(noRollbackFor = IllegalArgumentException.class)
public void process() {
    saveData();
    throw new IllegalArgumentException("Validation failed");
}


✔ Transaction will COMMIT, not rollback.

Multiple Exceptions
@Transactional(
    rollbackFor = {SQLException.class, IOException.class},
    noRollbackFor = {CustomBusinessException.class}
)

Real Banking Scenario
❌ Wrong
@Transactional
public void transfer() throws IOException {
    debit();      // deducted
    sendReceipt(); // IOException occurs
}


Money deducted ❌
Receipt failed ❌
Rollback NOT triggered ❌

✔ Correct
@Transactional(rollbackFor = IOException.class)
public void transfer() throws IOException {
    debit();
    sendReceipt();
}


Now full rollback ✔

Runtime vs Checked Quick Memory Trick
Exception Type	Rollback?
RuntimeException	✔ YES
NullPointerException	✔ YES
IllegalArgumentException	✔ YES
IOException	❌ NO
SQLException	❌ NO
Exception	❌ NO
Best Practice (Production)

Most teams use:

@Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)


So ALL failures rollback safely.

Interview Questions
Q1: Why Spring doesn’t rollback on checked exceptions by default?

Because checked exceptions are considered business exceptions, not system failures.

Q2: How to rollback for all exceptions?
@Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)

Q3: What happens if exception is caught?

If you catch exception and don’t rethrow, Spring WILL NOT rollback.

@Transactional
public void transfer() {
    try {
        debit();
        throw new RuntimeException();
    } catch (Exception e) {
        // swallowed ❌ → NO rollback
    }
}


✔ Fix:

catch (Exception e) {
    throw e;   // rethrow to trigger rollback
}

