🧠 4. Propagation (Transaction Behavior)
REQUIRED (Default)

What is Propagation?

Propagation defines how a method behaves when another transaction already exists.

REQUIRED (Default)
Rule

If transaction exists → join same transaction

If no transaction → create new transaction

👉 In simple words: “Use existing or create new”

Example
@Service
public class PaymentService {

    @Transactional   // REQUIRED (default)
    public void transfer() {
        debit();      // same transaction
        credit();     // same transaction
    }

    @Transactional
    public void debit() {
        // deduct money
    }

    @Transactional
    public void credit() {
        // add money
    }
}

Flow
transfer() → Transaction START
   ├── debit()  → joins SAME transaction
   ├── credit() → joins SAME transaction
transfer() → COMMIT / ROLLBACK


✔ Only ONE transaction exists
✔ If any step fails → full rollback

Failure Scenario
@Transactional
public void transfer() {
    debit();
    if (true) throw new RuntimeException("Failure");
    credit();
}


✔ Debit rolled back
✔ Credit not executed
✔ Data consistent

Real Banking Example
Transfer Money
 ├── Debit from A
 ├── Credit to B
 └── Save transaction log


All must succeed or ALL rollback → REQUIRED is perfect.

Important Interview Question
What happens if inner method fails?

Since both use same transaction, failure causes full rollback.

Common Mistake (Self Invocation)
@Transactional
public void transfer() {
    debit();   // ❌ proxy NOT used → no separate TX behavior
}


When calling method inside same class, Spring proxy is bypassed.
Propagation rules may not apply properly.

✔ Fix → move method to another @Service bean.

When REQUIRED is Best

Use when operations must be atomic:

Money transfer

Order placement

Payment processing

Inventory update

User registration

REQUIRED Behavior Summary
Situation	Result
No transaction exists	Create new
Transaction exists	Join same
Inner fails	Full rollback
Outer fails	Full rollback
Only one commit	Yes
Debug Log (Enable)
logging.level.org.springframework.transaction=TRACE


You’ll see:

Participating in existing transaction

Join existing or create new.

@Transactional
public void A() { B(); }

REQUIRES_NEW (Independent Tx)
@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
public void auditLog() {}


✔ Runs separate transaction
✔ Even if parent fails → audit saved

NESTED (Savepoint)
@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.NESTED)


Uses Savepoints

Partial rollback possible

SUPPORTS

Runs with tx if exists, else non-tx.

NEVER

Throws error if transaction exists.

🧠 5. Isolation Levels (Concurrency Control)

Isolation defines how one transaction is isolated from another concurrent transaction.

It controls data visibility + consistency when multiple users access same data.

Why Isolation Needed?

Without isolation:

Two users withdraw same money → double withdrawal

One transaction reads uncommitted data → dirty read

Same query returns different results → non-repeatable read

New rows appear during query → phantom read

Isolation prevents these problems.

4 Standard Isolation Levels

(From weakest ➜ strongest)

Level	Dirty Read	Non-Repeatable Read	Phantom Read	Performance
READ_UNCOMMITTED	❌ Possible	❌ Possible	❌ Possible	🚀 Fastest
READ_COMMITTED	✅ Prevented	❌ Possible	❌ Possible	Fast
REPEATABLE_READ	✅ Prevented	✅ Prevented	❌ Possible	Medium
SERIALIZABLE	✅ Prevented	✅ Prevented	✅ Prevented	🐢 Slowest
1️⃣ READ_UNCOMMITTED (Lowest)
What happens

Transaction can read uncommitted data from another transaction.

Problem → Dirty Read
T1 updates balance = 0 (not committed)
T2 reads balance = 0  ❌ wrong
T1 rolls back → actual balance = 1000


T2 read invalid data

⚠ Rarely used in real systems.

2️⃣ READ_COMMITTED (Most Common)

(Default in many DBs like PostgreSQL, Oracle)

Rule

Can only read committed data

✔ Prevents Dirty Read
❌ Allows Non-Repeatable Read

Problem → Non-Repeatable Read
T1 reads balance = 1000
T2 updates balance = 500 and commits
T1 reads again → 500 (changed)


Same query → different result.

3️⃣ REPEATABLE_READ (MySQL Default)
Rule

Row once read cannot change during transaction

✔ Prevents Dirty Read
✔ Prevents Non-Repeatable Read
❌ Phantom Read possible

Example
T1 reads account balance = 1000
T2 tries update → blocked OR version conflict
T1 still sees 1000


Great for banking systems.

4️⃣ SERIALIZABLE (Strongest)

Transactions behave like executed one-by-one (sequential).

✔ Prevents all:

Dirty Read

Non-Repeatable Read

Phantom Read

Example

If 100 users try withdrawal:

Only one runs at a time → fully safe.

⚠ Slowest → heavy locking → low performance.

Use only when absolute consistency required.

Spring Boot Usage
@Transactional(isolation = Isolation.READ_COMMITTED)
public void transferMoney() {
    // transfer logic
}

All Isolation Options in Spring
Isolation.READ_UNCOMMITTED
Isolation.READ_COMMITTED
Isolation.REPEATABLE_READ
Isolation.SERIALIZABLE
Isolation.DEFAULT   // DB default

