🧠 6. ReadOnly Transaction (Performance Boost)
A read-only transaction tells Spring & Hibernate:

“This transaction will NOT modify data — only read.”

So Hibernate:

Skips dirty checking

Skips flush

Avoids unnecessary locks

Uses optimized execution

➡ Result: Faster queries + Less memory + Better throughput

Normal vs ReadOnly Transaction
Normal Transaction
@Transactional
public Account getAccount(Long id) {
    return accountRepo.findById(id).orElseThrow();
}


Hibernate:

Tracks entity changes

Performs dirty checking

May flush before query

Higher overhead

ReadOnly Transaction
@Transactional(readOnly = true)
public Account getAccount(Long id) {
    return accountRepo.findById(id).orElseThrow();
}


Hibernate optimization:

❌ No dirty checking

❌ No flush

❌ No write lock

✔ Faster execution

Where to Use ReadOnly

Use for pure read operations only

Examples

✔ Balance check
✔ Transaction history
✔ Reports / Analytics
✔ User profile fetch
✔ Dashboard queries

Where NOT to Use

❌ Money transfer
❌ Insert / Update / Delete
❌ Ledger update
❌ Audit save

If you modify inside readOnly → changes may NOT persist

Internal Optimization (Important)

When readOnly = true:

Hibernate sets:

FlushMode = MANUAL


So:

No auto flush

No dirty checking

No update SQL generation

This is why performance improves.

Example — Banking Service
@Service
public class AccountQueryService {

    @Transactional(readOnly = true)
    public Double getBalance(Long accountId) {
        return accountRepo.findBalanceById(accountId);
    }

    @Transactional(readOnly = true)
    public List<Transaction> getStatement(Long accountId) {
        return txnRepo.findByAccountId(accountId);
    }
}

Performance Gain (Real World)
Case	Without ReadOnly	With ReadOnly
Memory usage	High	Low
Dirty checking	Yes	No
Flush	Yes	No
Speed	Normal	Faster
CPU	More	Less
Interview Questions
Q1: What does readOnly=true do?

Disables dirty checking & flush → improves performance.

Q2: Can we write inside readOnly transaction?

You can, but changes may not persist (not recommended).

Q3: Does it lock rows?

No write locks — better concurrency.

Q4: When to use?

Read-heavy operations.

Advanced Tip (Senior Level)

For heavy read systems:

Use readOnly = true

Use projections (DTO queries)

Use pagination

Use caching

Use index in DB

This combination gives massive performance boost
