🧠 7. Timeout (Prevent Long Locks)
What is Transaction Timeout?

timeout defines maximum time (in seconds) a transaction is allowed to run.

If transaction exceeds this time → Spring automatically rolls back.

@Transactional(timeout = 5)


Means:

Transaction must finish within 5 seconds or it will be rolled back

Why Timeout is Important?

Without timeout:

Long query may lock rows for long time

Other transactions get blocked

Thread pool gets exhausted

System becomes slow / hangs

With timeout:

Prevents long DB locks

Avoids deadlocks

Keeps system responsive

Auto rollback on slow query

Example
@Transactional(timeout = 3)
public void transfer(Long fromId, Long toId, double amount) {

    Account from = repo.findById(fromId).orElseThrow();
    Account to   = repo.findById(toId).orElseThrow();

    from.withdraw(amount);

    // Simulate slow DB call
    try { Thread.sleep(5000); } catch (Exception e) {}

    to.deposit(amount);
}

What happens?

Timeout = 3 sec

Code sleeps 5 sec

Spring throws:

TransactionTimedOutException


➡ Transaction ROLLBACK
➡ No money deducted
➡ No partial update

Real Banking Use Case

Use timeout in:

Money transfer

Ledger update

Bulk settlement

Payment processing

External API inside transaction

Example:

@Transactional(timeout = 10)
public void processPayment() { }

Default Timeout

If not set:

Timeout = -1 (No limit)


Which is dangerous in production.

Always define timeout for critical writes.

Timeout + Lock Example
@Transactional(timeout = 5)
@Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
public Account lockAccount(Long id) {
    return repo.findById(id).orElseThrow();
}


If row lock waits > 5 sec → rollback occurs → prevents long blocking.

Important Interview Questions
Q1: What happens when timeout occurs?

Spring throws TransactionTimedOutException and rolls back.

Q2: Does timeout cancel SQL query?

Depends on DB + driver. Usually transaction marked rollback-only.

Q3: Default timeout?

-1 (No timeout).

Q4: Why needed?

Prevent long locks, deadlocks, slow system.

Best Practice (Senior Level)

Use timeout in:

@Transactional(
    timeout = 5,
    isolation = Isolation.READ_COMMITTED,
    propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED
)


For:

Write-heavy operations

Lock-based queries

External API inside transaction

Batch processing

