🧠 8. Flush vs Commit (Important)

What is Flush?

Flush = Push SQL to DB (but NOT permanent)

Hibernate converts entity changes → SQL

Executes SQL in DB

But transaction is still open

Data can be rolled back

Entity → SQL → DB (temporary)


👉 Happens automatically before:

Commit

Query execution (sometimes)

Manual flush()

2. What is Commit?

Commit = Final Save (Permanent)

Ends transaction

Makes changes permanent

Cannot rollback after commit

Flush → Commit → Permanent save

Flush vs Commit — Key Difference
Feature	Flush	Commit
Sends SQL to DB	✅ Yes	✅ Yes
Makes data permanent	❌ No	✅ Yes
Can rollback	✅ Yes	❌ No
Ends transaction	❌ No	✅ Yes
Happens automatically	✅ Yes	✅ Yes
Example
@Transactional
public void transfer() {

    Account a = repo.findById(1L).get();
    a.setBalance(500);

    entityManager.flush();   // SQL executed but NOT permanent

    if(true) throw new RuntimeException();  // simulate error
}

What happens?

Flush sends UPDATE to DB

Exception occurs

Transaction ROLLBACK

Balance NOT updated ❌

👉 Because Flush ≠ Commit

Commit Example
@Transactional
public void transfer() {

    Account a = repo.findById(1L).get();
    a.setBalance(500);
}


When method ends normally:

Hibernate flushes automatically

Then commit happens

Data saved permanently ✅

When Hibernate Flushes Automatically?

Hibernate flush occurs:

Before Commit

Before executing JPQL/SQL query

When calling entityManager.flush()

Flush Modes (Advanced)
entityManager.setFlushMode(FlushModeType.AUTO);   // default
entityManager.setFlushMode(FlushModeType.COMMIT);

AUTO (Default)

Flush before commit + before queries

COMMIT

Flush only at commit → better performance

Real Banking Use Case

Flush useful when:

Need DB constraint validation early

Detect duplicate entry before commit

Batch processing

Prevent memory buildup in large loops

Example:

for(int i=0;i<10000;i++){
    repo.save(txn);
    if(i % 50 == 0){
        entityManager.flush();
        entityManager.clear();
    }
}


Used in high-performance batch inserts

Interview Questions (Very Important)
Q1: Does flush save data permanently?

❌ No. Only commit makes permanent.

Q2: Can rollback happen after flush?

✅ Yes.

Q3: When does Hibernate flush automatically?

Before commit and before queries (AUTO mode).

Q4: Why use manual flush?

Early validation

Batch performance

Memory control

Q5: Flush vs SaveAndFlush (Spring Data JPA)?
repo.save(entity);        // flush later
repo.saveAndFlush(entity); // flush immediately

Senior-Level Understanding

Transaction flow internally:

Start Transaction
   ↓
Modify Entity (Dirty Checking)
   ↓
Flush → SQL executed
   ↓
Commit → Permanent Save


If error occurs before commit → Rollback everything
Operation	Meaning
flush()	Sync to DB (not commit)
commit()	Permanent save
Demo
@Transactional
public void demo() {
    repo.save(acc);
    repo.flush();   // SQL executed here
}

🧠 9. Transaction Synchronization (After Commit Hook)
What is it?

Transaction Synchronization = Execute logic AFTER transaction commits successfully

Used when you want to:

Send Kafka event only if DB commit succeeds

Send email / notification after money transfer

Write audit log after transaction success

Avoid duplicate / inconsistent actions

👉 Prevents DB success but event failure problem

Why Needed?

Without synchronization:

@Transactional
public void transfer() {
    repo.save(txn);          // DB save
    kafka.send("TRANSFER");  // ❌ What if DB rolls back?
}


Problem:

Kafka sent ❌

DB rolled back ❌

Data inconsistency

Solution: After Commit Hook

Spring gives:

TransactionSynchronizationManager

Basic Example
import org.springframework.transaction.support.TransactionSynchronization;
import org.springframework.transaction.support.TransactionSynchronizationManager;

@Transactional
public void transfer() {

    repo.save(txn);

    TransactionSynchronizationManager.registerSynchronization(
        new TransactionSynchronization() {
            @Override
            public void afterCommit() {
                System.out.println("Transaction committed!");
                kafkaProducer.send("TRANSFER SUCCESS");
            }
        }
    );
}

Flow
Start TX
   ↓
DB Save
   ↓
Commit Success
   ↓
afterCommit() runs
   ↓
Kafka/Event/Email triggered


If rollback happens → afterCommit NOT executed

Key Hooks Available
Method	When Called
beforeCommit()	Just before commit
afterCommit()	After successful commit ✅
afterCompletion()	After commit OR rollback
beforeCompletion()	Before transaction ends
Real Banking Example
@Transactional
public void transfer(Long from, Long to, Double amount) {

    debit(from, amount);
    credit(to, amount);
    transactionRepo.save(txn);

    TransactionSynchronizationManager.registerSynchronization(
        new TransactionSynchronization() {
            @Override
            public void afterCommit() {
                notificationService.sendTransferSuccess(txn);
                kafkaProducer.publish(txn);
                auditService.log(txn);
            }
        }
    );
}


Guarantee:

If DB fails → No Kafka ❌

If DB commits → Kafka + Audit + Notification ✅

Interview Questions (Very Important)
Q1: Why use TransactionSynchronization?

To execute logic only after successful DB commit.

Q2: What happens if transaction rolls back?

afterCommit() will NOT execute.

Q3: Difference: @TransactionalEventListener vs Synchronization?
Feature	TransactionSynchronization	TransactionalEventListener
Low-level	Yes	No
Cleaner	No	Yes ✅
Recommended	❌	✅
Better Approach (Spring Recommended)
Using @TransactionalEventListener
Step 1 — Publish Event
applicationEventPublisher.publishEvent(new TransferEvent(txn));

Step 2 — Listen After Commit
@Component
public class TransferListener {

    @TransactionalEventListener(phase = TransactionPhase.AFTER_COMMIT)
    public void handle(TransferEvent event) {
        kafkaProducer.send(event.getTxn());
        auditService.log(event.getTxn());
    }
}


Cleaner + production-safe ✅

When to Use in Real Systems?

Kafka publish after DB commit

Audit logging

Email/SMS after transaction

Cache update after commit

Distributed transactions (Outbox pattern)

Common Mistake

❌ Calling Kafka/Email inside transaction
✔ Use After Commit Hook

